  "articleSummary": "This analytical article compares Git rebase and squash-merge workflows, ultimately arguing that squash-merging is the superior choice for team collaboration due to its simplicity and non-destructive nature. The author examines how different mental models of \"the commit\"—as either a rough checkpoint or a curated work of art—influence this technical preference, while critiquing the \"engineering theater\" and ego often associated with complex rebasing. Using a \"Deathmatch\" framing and a practical release-tagging scenario, the text highlights that rebasing often leads to redundant conflict resolution and broken collaboration links, whereas merging leverages Git’s advanced algorithms to minimize manual effort. The intended audience is professional software engineers and DevOps leads seeking to optimize team velocity and repository maintainability.",
